sentence: "The Russell 2000 Index (RUT), Nasdaq Composite (COMP), and Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJI) sold off today, perhaps on comments from Philadelphia Federal Reserve Bank President Charles Plosser," said Schaeffer's Trading Analyst Peter Bryans.
"It was another day where there were really no big economic data points that were released.
On the small-cap front, the RUT is right near its lows from early February of this year, and a break of this area could be significant."
After beginning the session just slightly lower, the Dow tumbled into the closing bell, settling with a triple-digit deficit.

Continue reading for more on today's market, including
• Short-term traders who placed bullish bets on Facebook Inc ( FB ) were likely interested to hear rumors of a new marketing partnership .
• Bullish speculators have been taking a notable interest in BlackBerry Ltd ( BBRY ) shares ahead of the company's quarterly earnings report next month.
• And in case you missed it , Schaeffer's contributor Adam Warner has some tips for trading CBOE Volatility Index (VIX) options , as the market's "fear gauge" continues to drift near historical lows.
• Plus ... A Fed official talks tapering, Microsoft Corporation ( MSFT ) unveils its new tablet, and General Motors Company ( GM ) option bears react to today's news.
Trading Topic of the Week -- How to Get Started with Options Learn how options pricing works .
Options pricing isn't rocket science, but it's not quite as straightforward as stocks (implied volatility, anyone?).
The Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJI - 16,374.31) gave back 137.6 points, or 0.8%, after notching an intraday low of 16,341.30 in mid-afternoon action.
Just three Dow components closed higher today, led by a 1.9% advance in The Home Depot, Inc. ( HD ) shares.
Intel Corporation (INTC) was unchanged on the day, and Caterpillar Inc. (CAT) paced the declining majority, down 3.6%.
The S&P 500 Index (SPX - 1,872.83) logged a 12.3-point drop, giving back 0.7% to slip back south of its 20-day moving average.
The tech-heavy Nasdaq Composite (COMP - 4,096.89) spent the day in the red as well, closing off 28.9 points, or 0.7%.
The CBOE Volatility Index (VIX - 12.96) moved higher amid the foundering benchmarks, ultimately settling on a gain of 0.5 point, or 4.4%.
The market's "fear gauge" overtook the 13 level in intraday trading -- hitting 13.30 -- but concluded the session below this threshold.
"There weren't any real positive signs from today's price action," added Bryans.
"It was mostly a 'risk-off' day, with high-beta names in the RUT and COMP showing continued weakness, despite some of the positive price action we saw yesterday and Friday.
Treasury prices traded higher, meanwhile, as rates declined.
Most of the major sectors were lower as well, as consumer discretionary and industrial names took the biggest hits.
Many market participants are likely looking forward to any new information that could be gleaned from the Federal Open Market Committee's meeting minutes, which get released tomorrow."

• Stocks took a turn for the worse today, after Philadelphia Fed President Charles Plosser opined that the central bank's current pace of curbing its monthly asset purchases might not be aggressive enough.
What's more, Plosser noted that a stronger U.S. economy could prompt a hike in interest rates "sooner rather than later."

(CNBC)
• First-quarter earnings at The Home Depot, Inc. ( HD ) were somewhat mixed , climbing year-over-year but falling short of analysts' estimates.
Specifically, sales rose 2.9% to $19.7 billion, while net earnings expanded by more than 12%.
Both figures, however, were below the Street's consensus estimate.
The retailer said it was impacted by the harsh winter conditions that extended into the early spring selling period.
Nevertheless, the stock pressed higher amid forward-looking optimism, and closed up 1.9%.

(Fortune)
• Microsoft Corporation ( MSFT ) debuted its Surface Pro 3 tablet in New York today.
The new device has a 12-inch screen, weighs less than two pounds, and is just 0.36 inches thick.
Five models will be priced from $799 to $1,949, depending on storage size, RAM, and other factors.

(USA Today)
• Fresh from a new annual high, Apple Inc. (AAPL) saw heavy trading on both sides of the fence today, as short-term speculators tried to predict the stock's next move.
• Put buyers eyed General Motors Company ( GM ) in the wake of another recall announcement.
For a look at today's options movers and commodities activity, head to page 2.
June oil futures fell slightly on the last day of trading, slipping 17 cents, or 0.2%, to $102.44 per barrel.
Meanwhile, the newly front-month July contract settled slightly higher on the day, adding 22 cents, or 0.2%, to $102.33 per barrel.
Tomorrow's weekly supplies report is expected to reveal a slight drop in crude inventories.
Gold futures edged slightly higher today, after spending the session in a narrow trading range.
By the close, June-dated gold had gained 80 cents, or 0.1%, to settle at $1,294.60 an ounce.
